03851nam a22006015i 9780674265943DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742659437 a10.4159/97806742659432doi  a(DE-B1597)664992  a(OCoLC)1250511794  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBD21 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a1902221 aMcDowell, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Engaged Intellect :bPhilosophical Essays /cJohn McDowell. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI Ancient Philosophy -- tII Issues in Wittgenstein -- tIII Issues in Davidson -- tIV Reference, Objectivity, and Knowledge -- tV Themes from Mind and World Revisited -- tVI Responses to Brandom and Dreyfus -- tBibliography -- tCredits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Engaged Intellect collects important essays of John McDowell. Each involves a sustained engagement with the views of an important philosopher and is characterized by a modesty that is partly temperamental and partly methodological. It is typical of McDowell to represent his own best insights either as already to be found in the writings of his heroes (Aristotle, Wittgenstein, Gadamer, and Sellars) or as inevitably emerging from a charitable modification of the views of those (such as Anscombe, Sellars, Davidson, Evans, Rorty, Dreyfus, and Brandom) subjected here to criticism. McDowell therefore develops his own philosophical picture in these pages through a method of indirection. The method is one of intervening in a philosophical dialectic at a characteristic juncture—in which it is difficult to avoid the feeling that further progress is required. McDowell shows how progress is to be achieved by preserving what is most attractive in the views of those he is in conversation with, while whittling away their weaknesses. As he practices this method, what emerges through the volume is the unity of McDowell’s own views. The combination of philosophical breadth with dialectical depth—of intricate argumentative detail with overall philosophical coherence—marks McDowell as one of the most compelling philosophers of our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674265943?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674265943423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674265943/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles